<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>Please Cease Invoking UO</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois2.cgi?The RealmWeaver">The RealmWeaver</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 4:50 p.m. 10/2/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> Please Cease Invoking UO<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/pvpquest/images/divider.gif" width=452 height=22 border=0></center><BR></STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#FFFFFF FACE=arial>
<P>EverQuest is not Ultima Online. EverQuest never will be Ultima Online. Ultima Online failed to deal with it's PK problems because it let them get out of hand first, and when it did attempt to implement systems to curtail the already rampant abuse, they were too little, and too late. Origin feared losing a customer base by putting more severe restrictions on its largest player community - the "KewlDoodz" as they have affectionately come to be known. The systems implemented on UO were not the problem, the timing and the manor in which they were imposed was the problem.

<P>In short, quit posting one-liners that say "Heh, sounds like UO!" or "They tried that on UO and failed," or "Gee, Ultima Online did the same thing and got nowhere." Ultima Online's problems were deep-rooted, and did not derive from the steps it tried to take to curtail PK abuse. In shorter, UO was doomed from the start, and posts saying "Boy, sounds like what they tried on UO!" do not add anything helpful, useful, or informative to the discussion on this board.
<P>[The RealmWeaver]
<P>dcc5500@rit.edu
<BR>ICQ#: 30795819
<BR>IM: WrldWeaver
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
